column1: This tab has one table with the air quality (micrograms of PM2.5 per cubic metre) from 2017-18 to 2022-23 for 81 monitoring sites around Australia. It ranges from cell A1 to H92.
Table 1 Air quality (micrograms of PM2.5 per cubic metre) 2017-18 to 2022-23.
Custom data request supplied by Department of Climate Change, Energy, the Environment and Water, July 2024

column3: Micrograms of PM2.5 per cubic metre

column1: * Indicates sites which did not meet the 75% coverage requirement for at least one quarter. Further details available at https://www.nepc.gov.au/nepms/ambient-air-quality.  Where data has been provided, it should be interpreted as being indicative only.

PM2.5 refers to particulate matter with a diameter of 2.5 micrometers (0.0025mm) or less. These very small particles are a common air pollutant and can be produced by smoke from fires, car and truck exhausts, and from industrial emmissions.
Data for Victoria for 2021-22 and 2022-23 is not yet available.

The data is sourced from jurisdictional monitoring undertaken in compliance with the National Environment Protection (Ambient Air Quality) Measure. The National Environment Protection Measure includes technical, performance and location requirements that must be met by monitoring stations.

Data is made public annually in National Environment Protection Council annual reports (https://www.nepc.gov.au/publications/annual-reports), however only data up until the 2018-19 period is publicly available at present. The subsequent data sets are unpublished and have been sourced directly; these are expected to be publicly available in the near future.
